segments.text: We had specific rules of engagement in which we were, let's say, restricted against certain types of targets and against certain types of tactics fighting.
You probably don't know that a fighter pilot flying over North Vietnam in war could not shoot down a North Vietnamese transport airplane that had North Vietnamese markings on it.
He was told categorically, you cannot shoot that airplane down.
We couldn't hit certain targets.
Get back to my subject.
Really, really, actually, we, the rules of engagement, read them specifically, you could not attack and fire at a North Vietnamese fighter unless it threatened you.
Now, that's the fact.
Are you kidding?
That's the fact.
That a fighter?
That a fighter.
Jeez.
That must have done wonders.
Really, really, really, we ignored this.
And, of course, you could see a fighter over there.
He was attacked.
How could anybody prove that he wasn't a threat to you?
Of course, you couldn't enforce that.
But the transport, you may have been diplomats in it.
Who knows?
Getting back to the dam, you couldn't bust these dams.
That would turn the water loose in North Vietnam and destroy the countryside.
We didn't want to do that.
I'm saying it's very sarcastic.
But the power, the powerhouse at that dam, it produced electricity.
We all tried to hit that.

But being about knowing how hydroelectric plants are with respect to dam, right adjacent to the dam, particularly the influx of water going down the chute, maybe 10 feet from the dam on the water side.
But how are you going to drop a lot of bombs and hit that without hitting the dam?
But we couldn't do that until we got the laser-guided bombs.

And I've actually seen pictures brought back where a laser-guided bomb was dropped two or three up and hit right in the funnel, 10-foot diameter funnel, of this hydroelectric plant and never even touched the dam.
That's how hateful it was.
I've seen bombs go through the roof of powerhouses right in the middle of Hanoi.
We've got pictures of it.
That was produced with Texas Instruments, and I'm proud to say that I was instrumental in getting that into the Air Force.
And when did we get the laser bomb?
Just about the time I left.
You mean in the Porsches?
Yeah.
Just about the time I came home in 1967.
So that was a great improvement.
Well, we've raised a lot of questions about this.
We were talking about problems.
We were talking about morale, and we were talking about some of the problems, and morale seems to be a major problem.
Well, it wasn't a real major problem.
It was one of the problems.
It was one of the problems, and how did you attempt to solve that problem?
It seems like it's a dilemma.
Improve our tactics and issues, and we did, and we cut down lost colonies at one time.
One of the...

It's ironic to say it, but one of the best ways we improved the morale of the boys over there was toward the end of the war when we finally got instructions above to bring the B-52s in and really bomb the place.
And you recall we did that.
And, you know, we lost one or two B-52s, sure.
But in that massive, up-to-date, drowned environment of modern SAM missiles, we sent
formation of the B-52s over and lost practically none.
A few, yeah.
But look at the effect of that bombing.
Had we done this initially in the war, that war wouldn't have lasted six months.
Now why would a carpet bombing of the B-52 versus your bombing from your fighters
Why do you say that that was more effective, and why couldn't they, why couldn't the SAM missiles hit those 52s like they could hit you?
Well, first, let's be sure we understand when you say carpet bombing.
When I say carpet bombing, I'm talking about the use of the B-52s against Viet Cong in South Vietnam.
Right, in the Ho Chi Minh Trail.
Yeah, and this was... Well, let's talk about... Now, the pinpoint bombing against targets by the B-52s
And North Vietnam was the same as the pinpoint bombing of the fighters, except, you know- Was it laser too?
No, not B-52.
It was just plain old B-52 bomb system bombing by radar or actual visual bombing.
Normal capability of B-52 as it is today to bomb.
They don't have the capability of laser bombs on a B-52?
Is it out of range or what?
No.
Matter of fact, while I was at TI, I brought this up, and I'm proud of the fact that we built a system to make a B-52 a smart bomber.
A smart bomber, in other words, a laser-guided bomb, and built equipment to put a B-52 to do the same thing.
It's just a matter of putting a laser on one of the aircraft so that he can mark the target with the same B-52, if you will, or another B-52 dropping laser-guided bomb.
The laser-guided bomb has to be
It was a special-equipped bomb with a laser homer on it.
Yeah, right.
Only built at TM.
Okay, so we had it on the fighters, but we didn't have it on the B-52s.
No, that's right.
Okay.
Now, why did we lose so many fighters over North Vietnam versus why did we not lose so many B-52s?
Well, why were the SAMs more effective against the fighters versus the B-52s?
Well, because of the fact that the fighters were the ones that were doing the bombing
when the SAMs were first brought in and had to experience and learn and stomach this type of aerial warfare initially.
We weren't using BPIC-2s at that time.
We weren't authorized to use them.
And through the experience of the fighters going through this, if you will, learning curve of tactics and techniques,
and new technology and evasive action.
Electronics.
We knew all of this before we ever threw the B-52s in, and we knew how to suppress the sounds.
That's the reason we didn't use any B-52s.
We used ECM.
And we go back to a famous statement by General LeMay, the bomber will always be able to get through to hit its target.
Well, this is true, but...
Under what conditions and how many losses are you going to accept?
Sure.
In other words, and correct me if I'm wrong, we would have started out with the bombings of the B-52s.
Instead of starting out with the fighters, we would have lost a lot of B-52s initially in 66 and 67.
You bet your boots.
Because we learned new tactics from the fighters in 66 and 67 before we threw the B-52s around 1970 at them.
Okay.
Definitely.
Okay.
Good.
Great.
Now, let's get back to morale.
Were there other ways that we tried to boost the morale of the pilots?
Other ways, like R&R?
Oh, man.
We built some of the finest facilities for the pilots you could ever imagine.
Tell me about it.
The staff that would come on visits from Washington were experienced TAC commanders.
Matter of fact,
General Dissway, commanding, well, General Dissway was very experienced in tactical.
The Tactical Air Force was back home.
Would come over and see our facilities in Thailand for living, where the pilots lived, barracks.
Actually, if you will, little cottages almost.
The maintenance facilities for the aircraft, air conditioning.
Beautiful equipment and all.
Top notch stuff.
And top notch, the cream of the crop.
Airmen, you know, polished it, were sent over there to fight the war, rightfully so.
Gee, I don't even have this at home.
So it was, and particularly, we even built a golf course, one of the basics.
No kidding.
It was a modified golf course, but even built one of those.
That's again, Jim Wilson.
So really, I'm overdoing the morale.
It wasn't, it was a problem.
And had we not done a lot of these things, it could have gotten worse.
I assure you this, we couldn't afford to keep losing aircraft like that.
We had to do some.

But here again, and I give General Momar and some of the previous commanders full credit, as well as the wing commanders, you know, it's a matter of staff people, planners, and operational people getting together and making decisions on how we would, you know,
revised tactics and all.

Any administrative problem with respect to the Thai Air Force or any, let's say, political problems in Thailand, now that is where I really came into the act at one of my functions, and objective and problem.
Let's get to that in just a minute.
I want to talk about the morale as far as enlisted men for the two years that you were there.
How was the morale as far as enlisted?
Great.
We took care of the enlisted men the same way.
And you know, as soon as you bring this question up, and I'll tell you right now, when I was there in Thailand in 1966 and 67, I don't remember
I don't remember in my staff meetings, my personnel, staff man, ever bringing up the problem of drugs and marijuana.
I don't remember this at all.
Now, this is in Thailand.
See, we didn't have Viet Cong that might come in and cover a base at night.
So the morale of our boys, it was a considerably easier situation living in Thailand than it was in South Vietnam at an air base.
Was there any security problems where you ever attacked?
Never.
And the Thai Air Forces, by the way, was at each base.
They were responsible for your security.
They were responsible for base defense.

Now, we did have a few, much evidence in North, around Udorn and Ubon, North and East Thailand, and particularly Nakhon Phanom, where there was evidence of, let's say, Pathet Lao, Laotian, which would count, you know, tantamount to Viet Cong.
making probe attempts to enter the base, but I don't recall ever an attack on a base in Thailand.
None like there were in South Vietnam.
And there was never an American airman or pilot shot at or shot, killed in Thailand, to your memory?
No.
Not from a standpoint of warfare, no.
OK. And no drugs.
That is surprising.
As a matter of fact, when I, you know, subsequent to being out of service and back home and seeing, reading what I did, I just don't recall any having any problems like that.
If they were, they were never brought to my attention, but certainly not on a scale that I have since read about in South Vietnam.
But it's different, and you know, the poor old army, the life they lived in the jungles in South Vietnam, that must have been horrible.

Now, before we get to the relations that you had with the Thais on a high level, let's talk about the relations that your junior officers and your enlisted men had with the Thais just going out to base on liberty.
Oh, no.
No problem.
No problem.
There was, to answer your question, really no problem at that level.
No.
How long have you been with that water code?
Do you want me to change anything?
Turn it off.
Turn it off.
The real problem was, let's say, the economic effect on the country of Thailand that the political levels, the administrations of Thailand, was confronted with.
The influx of money.
Thais worked in support roles on the base and then having more money than you take a stick at, unusual.
They go back home.
And then, naturally, it's developed a black market type of an operation with PX supplies and this type of a thing.
And inflation.
And inflation, oh yeah.
And it had an impact, see.
The Thai people weren't used to this type of thing.
For instance, we had to build barracks and had to build them fast at Udorn.
Well, we just put out a... We didn't have the American forces to do that.
Use a saw and hammer.
So we put out an advertisement in Udorn.
Show up at the gate tomorrow morning with a saw and hammer and we'd hire you as a carpenter.
Rice growers that couldn't even saw would show up with a brand new saw and a brand new hammer at the gate.
We hired them.
In 48 hours, we trained him as a carpenter, and he did well.
Did they?
That type of thing.
Did they have more hard workers?
Oh, yeah.
The people of the street, they loved it.
They had no problem whatsoever.
Of course, you had prostitution, but you had that throughout the world.
That was no problem.
Venereal disease really was not too great a problem.
The medical problems, by the way, were not great.
We had no real medical problems.
Clean.
Clean.
Well, we kept it clean.
Yeah.
And I give General Wolfe a full credit for it.
Boy, he was a monster when it came to uncleanliness.
And when you hired these people to come in and build your base, you had American supervisors, of course.
Oh, yeah.
They just nailed away.
Oh, yeah.
Oh, yeah.
What did you pay them?
Did you pay them a lot more than they could make?
No, no, see that's one of the things that was coordinated at the political level.
You couldn't go much above what the going rate was, otherwise it cost such enough people, but still it was more money than they'd ever seen before.
Do you remember about how much it was a day?
No, no I don't.
All I know is it was carefully figured and controlled.
Okay, so for the two years you were in there, it sounds like enlisted morale was high.
Oh, with no real problem.
Okay.
Now let's talk about a headache that you had, or a challenge anyway, and that is the relations with the Thai officials.
Well, if I had a problem, in other words.
I thought you said that you had some problems as far as relations with Tide, which was another part of your duties and functions.
The economic problem and political problem is one of the things I just described here.
It wasn't an insurmountable and great problem, but it was one of the problems that required my attention.
So what about the politics of dealing with the king, the queen, and other high military officials?
I had to keep Air Marshal Boonshue, the Chief of Staff.
How do you spell that?
I'll correct it.
It's almost the way it sounds.
B-O-U-N-C-H-O-U something, G-G something like that.
In a lot of these things, I suggest, well, in your history, you probably want to spell it accurately, and I'll try it.
I think in my papers I have the exact spelling.
You'll find something.
Because that would be impossible for my gal to spell these words.
Oh, yeah.
But I'd keep him informed of our, if we brought in some additional replacements or aircraft, I'd keep him informed.
And a lot of times, by the way I did this, I would do it through what we called the American MAG Forces, Military Assistance Group, which was stationed right in Bangkok.
And their primary mission
was to support and train the Thai Air Forces.
And many times, me being up at Udorn, I'd just get on the phone and call the colonel heading up that group and tell him about this problem.
And since he was dealing daily across the board with the Thai Air Force staff, he could really handle this problem easily for me.

It was only major things where I'd have to take a trip down to Thailand and maybe even get with the ambassador that would require my attention to go across maybe to the ambassador to talk with somebody at the Thai governmental level, like the prime minister, maybe Air Marshal Da Wee or somebody like that.
An example maybe, huh?
What would it be?
Let me see.
Oh, yes.
The

at the high, of course, international diplomatic level, Thailand trying to play their cards as carefully as possible and not get North Vietnamese invading Thailand, they would never admit openly, publicly, that American aircraft were operating on Thai bases.
Everybody in the world knew this, but they could not openly admit this to the media, the correspondents.
And correspondents were always trying to get them to admit this.
And even though correspondents could see them flying home?
Well, correspondents weren't, uh, they were controlled pretty well through, uh, throughout
bases of Thailand, they were pretty well restricted to Bangkok, and you know, making the inquiries right there in Bangkok.
I guess I've seen, I guess during my fifteen months over there, or eighteen months, I guess I saw in brief correspondence at my air base in Udon, maybe twice.
And once, when we finally agreed, and here again was a careful coordination with the Thais, it wasn't a problem, but it was solving a problem.
Money Thailand was going to announce, I agree, announce publicly that the American players were operating from their base.
We had a big, open meeting with the correspondents at Tockley, up in Corotta, Tockley, Tockley.
And I got up and, you know, officially announced it.
And the problem went away then.
The media, I just want to be able to say it.
They weren't bugged after that.
Do you call that a problem?
Really not.
It's just something that had to be lived with.

Whenever the king and queen made an official visit throughout Thailand, let's say in the upper reaches of Thailand to the hinterland, particularly during the months of the heavy flooding of the Kong River, they wanted to show up to boost the morale of the people.
I would provide helicopters
for them.
With American or tied insignia?
American helicopters and American insignia.
No kidding.
And they'd fly them out and they wouldn't change the insignia?
See, we had some helicopter portraits of our own anyhow, but so did the Ties.
But a Tied King would fly in a foreign helicopter?
Sure, there's no problem about that.
Well, I mean, he wouldn't even change the insignia.
No, no.

I'd say, see, I'd fly him out of Udorn, maybe 20, 30 miles north up along the banks of the Mekong River, still in Thailand, and land in the, let's say, in a little island in the middle of the flooded area where a lot of the people have congregated.
Then he'd get out and walk among the people and bow and scrape and show reverence.
And, oh, this was a great thing.
And then he'd get back in the airplane and bring it back to Udorn.
There was never even talk about insignia on the airport.
The people were just happy to see their royalty.
That's right.
In Thailand, number one is religion.
Number two is the king and queen.
Number three is, well, what else?
The king and queen are very important.
You know, you realize a lot of coups in Thailand, but the king and queen are always there.
And Thailand is always there.
But it's the lower structure that has changed.
and most of the time it's pretty well infused with military people.
Surprisingly, Thailand has survived through the Japanese invasion.
It's still intact and so forth.
Okay, so back to the relations with the Thais.
How about just working with the Thailanis?
How about just working with the people?
The military people?
Yeah.
How were relations between American generals and Thai generals?
Excellent.
Excellent.
Matter of fact, we have a healthy respect for one another, and I was proud of this.
The comments about the capabilities is another thing.
Let's talk about that later on, the military capabilities.
But our relations with them was terrific.
Their morale was great.
we really had a healthy respect for one another.
I think in a lot of cases the Thai Air Force officers were delighted that this vast American bomber machine was operating their bases.
Look at the experience they were getting just watching this.
Look at the experience they were getting.
One of the, wasn't really a problem, but it was something I had to
carefully monitor and be very careful about was the so-called air defense of Thailand.
See here where the American forces on these bases in Thailand and for all practical purposes the Thais didn't have any air defense.
They had a few F-86s which were really air defense type aircraft but very few
But here we had all these F-4s and F-105s.
And let's say that the North Vietnamese suddenly maybe wanted to attack in our base in Thailand.
Who would defend against this?
Well, the Thais knew we had a better capability.
As a matter of fact, we were operating with key radars.
for, you know, controlling the oil.
No kidding?
You were operating their radars?
No.
You were operating the key radars on the base?
The key radar sites.
Yeah, on the bases.
On the bases, but eventually we turned them over to the Thais and the Thais were operating them.
Because really we didn't fear an air defense tactical situation in Thailand.
to a great extent, didn't fear an air defense tactical situation in South Vietnam.
It was a matter of, you know, the North Vietnamese forces had an air defense force.

But there were some helicopter operations every once in a while across the river from Laos into Thailand, and we'd pick them up on a radar, and naturally we had to scramble something to intercept them.
Most of this was at night.
I think, looking back now, that a lot of this was plain smuggling.
by who knows, whether it was the Pathet Lao, or Viet Cong, or North Vietnamese, or maybe even Thais smuggling gold, or marijuana, or what have you, dope across from Laos to Thailand.
But I remember talking to Marshal Boonshue to coordinate and get it understood that
and actually on paper and meet General, get General Momar's approval of my responsibilities in Thailand for air defense.

Now, I reported to General Momar tactically, so I had to be responsible for air defense of our American forces in Thailand at these Thai air bases, and that's the reason I had a control center in my headquarters, an air defense control center, really a tactical air control center.
What was the plan?
The North, let's say the North Vietnamese sent over a few MiGs to hit out one of your air bases.
What was the plan?
Who would scramble?
The Americans or the Thais or both?
No, I would.
How did it work?
I would.
I'd scramble.
This is one of the things that I resolved with Air Marshal Boonshue.
He gave, Air Marshal Boonshue actually gave me authority.
And orally, he told me one time, you have authority to shoot these aircraft down if you want to.
And I asked him to
give me this in writing, and he wouldn't do it.
But if it came to that problem, I don't think I was worried about any such thing as that.
As a matter of fact, on two occasions, on two occasions, we picked up a blip on our radar right there at Udorn in the northern ridges of Thailand, and I had no, see we got
We knew air traffic.
We'd given this from Seventh Air Force.
We knew if there was going to be any tactical airplanes in the area.
Matter of fact, we would drive the room where the bombers right over were going on the way up.
We picked up this, I was called out of bed about 2 o'clock in the morning and rushed down to the control center and getting in.
Actually, I went over to the radar site, which is right on the same bay, and saw the blip.
And I got in my control center and I let some of the Air Force know immediately, personally, is there anything there?
No, sir, we don't have anything.
Well, that blip went right straight over the top of Udorn.
Of course, we were attacked.
Went right on down, disappeared to the south.
And on over south.
So you didn't scramble?
No.
Well, we scrambled.
No, we didn't scramble.
Why not?
We didn't have any fighters right at Udorn.
But I was prepared to tell Korat and Takli to travel to that floor if necessary.
Now later on, we did get- And you never found out what this month was?
No, but I'm convinced what it was.
It could have been a high altitude SR-71 or U-2 on reconnaissance that we didn't even know about.
Maybe even Seventh Air Force didn't even know about it.
I don't know.
It was way out there though.
But later on, you said.
But later on, we got a little bit concerned about such situations.
So we actually had two F-102s stationed at Udorn on air defense alert, strictly an air defense operation.
And this element came out of a F-102 interceptor squadron over at Philippines Clark Air Force Base.
And of course, I monitored their operation.
To my knowledge, I
We may have scrambled those guys maybe once or twice against a suspected attack, either night or day during a time of the war, maybe once or twice.
Now, what were the TIE capabilities?
It sounds like we've covered relations with the TIE.
It sounds great.
What about the capabilities of their Air Force and their military in general?
I'd say the capabilities of the entire Air Force was typical of those small countries in the Far East.
Their equipment was, you know, definitely obsolete.
We finally gave them, just about time I left, we programmed two or three F-5, modern fighter, if you will, two or three.
Now they had three or four squadrons of
jet aircraft, F-86 type.
By that time, it was obsolete.
And some little T-26s, which was nothing more but a prop-driven trainer airplane.
But their mission really was, I mean, the equipment in our MAG, Military Assistance Group, function, which was done in Thailand, I mean, Bangkok, which wasn't under me.
It went straight to, you know, back to the USF headquarters, but coordinated with me.
Their mission, of course, was to train and equip the Thai Air Force in accordance with really what their threat was.

Well, really the only threat at that time in Thailand was insurrection, possibly spilling of the Pathit Lao bit-kong, if you will, Lao's type bit-kong, Pathit Lao, the bad guy, if you will, spilling across the river and causing trouble in Thailand.
Thailand amongst the natives, and maybe even sabotaging roads, and particularly against the Thai police.
The Thai police were greatly involved in security throughout Thailand.
It was always a matter of whether the Thai army was going to do it, whether the Thai police was going to do it.
And actually, we equipped the Thai police, you might call them national police, with helicopters.
But they didn't have any problems as far as that when you were there, as far as insurgency.
Oh, yes, sir.

As a matter of fact, my coordination with the Thais was primarily at the base level, and that's where the Thai base commander and the American base commander coordinated their relations with one another, particularly on any possible security measures or security threats.
Now, the main place we had this problem
was at my base at Udorn and at Mekong Phnom, way over by the Mekong River in extreme, well around the Mekong River on the border of Laos and Thailand and northeastern part of the country.
Actually, there was constant jungle battles between suspected
North Vietnamese communists, if you will, insurrectionists, and the Thai police, the Thai army, continually.
And there was ambushes and all.
Much like what the South Vietnamese and the United States Army was involved in in South Vietnam.
But not definitely, definitely not on that scale.
There was even some possibility we wondered about up northern, in extreme northern Thailand, of maybe Chinese infiltration.
But we never could prove that.
So you equipped the Thai police with helicopters?
Yep.
The United States Air Force.
Sure.
One of Ambassador Graham's primary objectives at the time I was over there was to, I think, get around 10 or 15 helicopters for the Thai Air Forces.
He eventually succeeded, but
And this gets into another interesting area between McNamara.
We'll get to that.
OK.
It sounds to me that we've done a fairly good job on the relations with the tithes, morale, your functions and duties.
Is there any other types of duties that you were involved with?
Yes.
One of them ought to be brought out and can be brought out now.

There were some very specious at that time and highly classified operations being carried out in Laos and as ironic as it sounds and as unusual as it might sound to you and just can't understand it, there was a so-called Air America
outfit on Udorn Air Force Base, right in my headquarters.
Those people were really controlled and, if you will, managed and directed really by the American Ambassador of Laos at that time, Ambassador Sullivan.
But there they were at Udorn Air Force Base in Thailand.
How did I fit into that?
Finally, I got through Ambassador Sullivan.
I actually made trips across the river to his, to his embassy at times.
And frankly, in a way, there was no charter for me there.
I just liked General McConnell told me to use your head, and I developed a very close rapport with Ambassador Sullivan, and I liked him
I assure you, I assure you, that he was not like the Seventh Air Force.
From General Momar right on down.
He was not liked by them?
Not liked.
As a matter of fact, General Momar made a special trip up to my headquarters and to talk to Ambassador Sullivan.
At my suggestion, look, you two guys better get together.
I realized what the problem was.
But Ambassador Sullivan was operating, in effect,
Let's put it out on the table.
CIA forces as Air America.
General Mollmeyer had nothing to do with this.
But General Mollmeyer objected to this.
Here's one air power commander over there, and I'm sure that Spike is his nickname.
I'm sure he went to USAAF headquarters through channels to talk about this, as well as the Navy problem, controlling Navy air, you know, Navy strikes against North Vietnam to coordinate the air.
But he never got the first base on me.
And I agree with him wholeheartedly.
But there I was on the spot, and I had to coordinate all this activity.
Well, they- So you had to coordinate the activity between the CIA Air America and your own Air Forces?

I would- You know, as a result of being there, and like Gentleman McConnell told me, use your head, I knew that some way or another I was going to have to do this, at least keep General Mulmire informed.
Well, this was impossible.
Why?
Because of the CIA.
The ambassador wouldn't give you any, he wouldn't tell you anything about Aram or what their mission was?
No, and he didn't have any responsibility or instructions to do it.
Oh, I knew about Aram.
He finally granted me authority just by sheer rapport that I developed with him.
He finally granted me authority to maintain relations and actually cleared me to sit in his control center
at Air America where I knew about the operations of all the helicopters.
At Udorn.
At Udorn, yeah.
And I had access to it.
It turned out to be not a real great problem up in the area with respect to Air America because there were nothing more but supply missions.
Is that what they were doing?
Yeah, carrying supplies to the General Mao and his forces that were fighting the North Vietnamese in the path of Laos.
really supply missions, really what they were.
By helicopter.
By helicopter.
And a few transport aircraft, like C-123s.
But when we got into the- From Udorn.
From Udorn.

But when we got into the operations of some of the T-26 type aircraft, which had a tactical capability to drop bombs, and this was a Laotian Air Force, maybe let's say 15 or 20 T-26s, to coordinate their activities,
along the Ho Chi Minh Trail in Laos.
And their objective, of course, was the same as our Seventh Air Force, was to stop supplies down the trail and fight the insurrectness in Laos.

So we had to help, but the idea when you get airplanes in the air and they begin to show up on your blips and your radar and your air defense system, you've got to know where they are and who they are, or you're going to get in trouble and shoot your own airplanes down.

So this is where you had to actually do some coordination, particularly when we got the special forces, and this again, now this was under me and General Beaumont, our 7th Air Force, a B-26 type airplane, an old B-26, which was propeller driven twin engine and could carry some bombs and some helicopters, the big heavy helicopters, the H-53,

special forces assigned over in the Konvenom and built up that force really in support of Ambassador Sullivan's forces and objectives and requirements in Laos, but here it's based in the Konvenom in Tuckland.
